xml:lang="zh-x-oc">bi lʰaʔ b-raal</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">bi ɕɣɛ lɑ</pron></form><sense xml:id="uuid-328d8300-06b2-4513-9c89-f775725593ae"><gramGrp><pos>N</pos><tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func><tls:sem-feat corresp="#uuid-2e7204ae-4771-435b-82ff-310068296b6d">buddhist</tls:sem-feat></gramGrp><def>BUDDH: the family name of the Ninth Indian Patriarch 佛陀難提</def></sense></entry><entry type="word" xml:id="uuid-11425f80-b589-4630-bf0e-ddc690bdf68d"><form corresp="#uuid-0029c246-382f-4465-abf0-e562ce8699ef #uuid-29be220c-b19f-4f4a-9bfd-fdbcc657dc22 #uuid-638f5102-6260-4085-891d-9864102bc27c"><orth>脅尊者</orth><pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">xié zūn zhě</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-oc">qhlob tsuun kljaʔ</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">hi̯ɐp tsuo̝n tɕɣɛ</pron><listBibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-2389c812-8053-4187-8f7a-19f6e856050f">FOGUANG</ref><title>佛光大辭典 Fóguāng dàcídiǎn The Foguang Dictionary of Buddhism</title><biblScope unit="page">4289c</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl></listBibl></form><sense xml:id="uuid-fe47c2ef-574f-4b62-b90f-acfdf8018d09"><gramGrp><pos>N</pos><tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func><tls:sem-feat corresp="#uuid-c6e8e102-3129-49f0-a97e-618026f7676d">meaning</tls:sem-feat></gramGrp><def>BUDDH: skr. Venerable Pārśva, the 10th Indian Patriarch in the Chan/Zen tradition (phon. transliteration is 波栗溼縛 or 波奢; also referred to as Xié bǐqiū 脅比丘, Xié Luóhàn 脅羅漢, Chánglǎo Xié 長老脅[CA]</def></sense></entry><entry type="word" xml:id="uuid-e188b285-4cef-4e6f-9420-f82282656367"><form corresp="#uuid-0b8dea74-8a9e-4899-b1a2-38988a4d58dc #uuid-3ab9d40a-65e0-4583-94d7-dfde6cb1f504 #uuid-04dd5388-2dab-4fd8-9f3f-554c4e967b4b #uuid-a07df213-b938-43db-9782-7161ec468c87"><orth>伏馱密多</orth><pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">fú tuó mì duō</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-oc">bɯɡ daal mbriɡ k-laal</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">buk dɑ mit tɑ</pron></form><sense xml:id="uuid-b4191493-eb35-478d-82ab-7efe15e4d8f2"><gramGrp><pos>N</pos><tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func><tls:sem-feat corresp="#uuid-2e7204ae-4771-435b-82ff-310068296b6d">buddhist</tls:sem-feat></gramGrp><def>BUDDH: the Ninth Indian Patriarch in the Chan/Zen tradition (more common is the transliteration Fótuómìduō 佛陀蜜多)</def></sense></entry><entry type="word" xml:id="uuid-06db2202-c2df-48cb-9530-2f4b1a507eed"><form corresp="#uuid-d47e7bd5-88a4-4216-b6ee-b266d66dd08c #uuid-8a3817af-ba46-4d61-9a19-ff72fd8a0a0b #uuid-212cd790-45ca-42a7-a8dd-0d7ff96127ac #uuid-a07df213-b938-43db-9782-7161ec468c87"><orth>佛陀蜜多</orth><pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">fó tuó mì duō</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-oc">bɯd laal mbiɡ k-laal</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">bi̯ut dɑ mit tɑ</pron></form><form corresp="#uuid-0b8dea74-8a9e-4899-b1a2-38988a4d58dc #uuid-3ab9d40a-65e0-4583-94d7-dfde6cb1f504 #uuid-04dd5388-2dab-4fd8-9f3f-554c4e967b4b #uuid-a07df213-b938-43db-9782-7161ec468c87"><orth>伏馱密多</orth><pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">fú tuó mì duō</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-oc">bɯɡ daal mbriɡ k-laal</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">buk dɑ mit tɑ</pron></form><sense xml:id="uuid-67d76226-5f96-4b08-8df3-7daabba2d76c"><gramGrp><pos>N</pos><tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func><tls:sem-feat corresp="#uuid-2e7204ae-4771-435b-82ff-310068296b6d">buddhist</tls:sem-feat></gramGrp><def>BUDDH: The Ninth Indian Patriarch in the Chan/Zen tradition (in ZTJ transliterated 伏馱密多; other transliterations include 伏馱蜜多, Fótuómìduōluó 佛陀蜜多羅, Fótuómì 佛陀蜜; also referred to as Juéqīn 覺親) (he was a person from 提伽國 and his family name was Písheluó 毘舍羅; his teacher was Fótuónántí 佛陀難提; his was known for his wisdom and for his abilities to teach and convert people, including the 'heretical' teachers at the court of the king); skr. Buddhamitra</def></sense></entry><entry type="word" xml:id="uuid-8b5d51ab-ae81-498b-9708-c63d9004965d"><form corresp="#uuid-d47e7bd5-88a4-4216-b6ee-b266d66dd08c #uuid-8a3817af-ba46-4d61-9a19-ff72fd8a0a0b #uuid-e789dee5-fd16-4331-bd2b-749ed2f16a58 #uuid-f7792e89-6029-42e2-999d-b6f8cf133e7c"><orth>佛陀難提</orth><pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">fó tuó nán tí</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-oc">bɯd laal mɢlaan ɡ-lee</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">bi̯ut dɑ nɑn dei</pron><listBibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-2389c812-8053-4187-8f7a-19f6e856050f">FOGUANG</ref><title>佛光大辭典 Fóguāng dàcídiǎn The Foguang Dictionary of Buddhism</title><biblScope unit="page">2641c</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-80b363d9-8859-464e-b531-474775c06186">SOOTHILL</ref><title>A Dictionary of Chinese Buddhist Terms</title><biblScope unit="page">229</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl></listBibl></form><sense xml:id="uuid-ae84c42b-fda1-4d55-8dd1-526091234d04"><gramGrp><pos>N</pos><tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func><tls:sem-feat corresp="#uuid-2e7204ae-4771-435b-82ff-310068296b6d">buddhist</tls:sem-feat></gramGrp><def>BUDDH: skr. Buddhanandi, the eighth Indian Patriarch in the Chan/Zen tradition (he was a person from 迦摩羅國)</def></sense></entry><entry type="word" xml:id="uuid-03db1ce2-a2f4-402f-b5ca-699c178bfe83"><form corresp="#uuid-aff96f35-56cd-4319-a52d-054402822438 #uuid-1f787b7a-da56-4bc1-a3da-8c894d65d555 #uuid-e789dee5-fd16-4331-bd2b-749ed2f16a58 #uuid-f7792e89-6029-42e2-999d-b6f8cf133e7c"><orth>僧迦難提</orth><pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">sēng jiā nán tí</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-oc">sɯɯŋ kraal mɢlaan ɡ-lee</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">səŋ kɣɛ nɑn dei</pron><listBibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-e5b8d747-4092-4c37-a4af-f74a2c5140ba">YANAGIDA 1990</ref><title>祖堂集 Sodōshū Zutang ji Daijō butten 大乘佛典</title><biblScope unit="page">354, fn.107</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl></listBibl></form><sense xml:id="uuid-5f93ae06-758a-4f2d-b30b-5415cd233935"><gramGrp><pos>N</pos><tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func><tls:sem-feat corresp="#uuid-2e7204ae-4771-435b-82ff-310068296b6d">buddhist</tls:sem-feat></gramGrp><def>BUDDH: the Seventeenth Indian Patriach in the Chan/Zen tradition; skr. Sa%nghanadī (also referred to as Zho5nghé 眾河)</def></sense></entry><entry type="word" xml:id="uuid-d97bbdcb-1926-48e0-a299-9c6b9a70efac"><form corresp="#uuid-ce5dfd21-7d74-4fe9-9abb-f28f250a6144 #uuid-559016e6-7996-4e7b-bb4a-e5f8c2e4247a #uuid-2681e56e-ff78-4a69-8d0e-b83326d26f1b #uuid-ef8eb44d-db8a-4f3b-8eaf-a0dec0116c4a"><orth>商那和修</orth><pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">shāng nà hé xiū</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-oc">qhjaŋ naals ɡool sqlɯw</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">ɕi̯ɐŋ nɑ ɦʷɑ sɨu</pron><listBibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-2389c812-8053-4187-8f7a-19f6e856050f">FOGUANG</ref><title>佛光大辭典 Fóguāng dàcídiǎn The Foguang Dictionary of Buddhism</title><biblScope unit="page">4407c-4408b</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl></listBibl></form><sense xml:id="uuid-7966bf20-da46-45b7-8c3e-d70560be404b"><gramGrp><pos>N</pos><tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func><tls:sem-feat corresp="#uuid-2e7204ae-4771-435b-82ff-310068296b6d">buddhist</tls:sem-feat></gramGrp><def>BUDDH: the 'Third Indian Patriarch' of the Chan/Zen  School; skr. Śāṇa-vāsin, pali Sāṇa-vāsī; other transcriptions include: Shēnàpósī 奢那婆斯, Shěnàbōsī 舍那波私, Shěnàhéxiū 舍那和修, Shěnàpósī 舍那婆斯, etc. translations of the name include: 胎衣, 自然衣, 麻衣 (he was a disciple of Ananda; according to legend he remained in the womb of his mother for six years; after he had become a discpiple of Ananda he demonstrated his excellent abilities to remember the teachings of the Buddha; he was also known for converting dragons and all kinds of supernatural powers which he used for converting people)</def></sense></entry><entry type="word" xml:id="uuid-c9c452ef-7062-4839-b2f6-8a97b60f7f69"><form corresp="#uuid-f3cdf9db-509f-4926-b2b0-23f4035ecf61 #uuid-a07df213-b938-43db-9782-7161ec468c87 #uuid-73b6e4e2-147a-4ead-8d0b-386283e2a333"><orth>若多羅</orth><pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">rě duō luó</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-oc">njaʔ k-laal b-raal</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">ȵɣɛ tɑ lɑ</pron><listBibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-2389c812-8053-4187-8f7a-19f6e856050f">FOGUANG</ref><title>佛光大辭典 Fóguāng dàcídiǎn The Foguang Dictionary of Buddhism</title><biblScope unit="page">4303</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl></listBibl></form><sense xml:id="uuid-a2ed81af-6b7f-49c6-b359-0f56da79d620"><gramGrp><pos>N</pos><tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func><tls:sem-feat corresp="#uuid-2e7204ae-4771-435b-82ff-310068296b6d">buddhist</tls:sem-feat></gramGrp><def>BUDDH: skr. Prajñātāra, a monk from Eastern India, in the Zen tradition regarded as 27th Indian Patriarch (for a biographic entry see ZTJ 1.062,07; WU/GU: 38; FO: 75)</def></sense></entry><entry type="word" xml:id="uuid-6c14b844-d5bd-426e-93b4-19469e7a2be1"><form corresp="#uuid-d4b04ba5-1c96-47af-aea6-fabbc6989ff0 #uuid-f7792e89-6029-42e2-999d-b6f8cf133e7c #uuid-caaece51-86d5-4d35-a2a4-ca05027ce6e1 #uuid-62efd968-fcbb-4774-9c42-a22187c35c91"><orth>菩提達摩</orth><pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">pú tí dá mó</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-oc">bɯ ɡ-lee daad maal</pron><pron xml:lang="zh-x-mc">buo̝ dei dɑt mʷɑ</pron><listBibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-088cbd14-02f7-4480-92b7-b6d0046e9a2d">ERRU SIXING LUN(A)</ref><title>二入四行論 Èrrù sìxíng lùn Treatise on the Two Entries and Four Practices</title><note><p/></note></bibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-87e3c9d9-977b-4a25-a79f-2cdff4298207">ERRU SIXING LUN(B)</ref><title>二入四行論 Èrrù sìxíng lùn Treatise on the Two Entries and Four Practices</title><note><p/></note></bibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-cdc2bb7d-47ff-4184-af95-ddb739d8783e">ERRU SIXING LUN(C)</ref><title>二入四行論 Èrrù sìxíng lùn Treatise on the Two Entries and Four Practices</title><note><p/></note></bibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-5ed01248-717b-4a3d-9b6a-9fc0921f58ce">FAURE 1986B</ref><title>Bodhidharma as Textual and Religious Paradigm History of Religions</title><note><p/></note></bibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-22e48910-6b95-4c98-8baa-7a424c6feb0e">FAURE 1993</ref><title>Chan Insights and Oversights</title><biblScope unit="page">130-135</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-392f9c5a-fe79-4c47-85a9-4be7cb9b6dc0">MCRAE 1986</ref><title>The Northern School and the Formation of Early Ch'an Buddhism</title><biblScope unit="page">17-18, 43-44, 85-86</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-64d2e9f4-1306-45bf-8d0b-64702410f4c0">XUGAOSENGZHUAN</ref><title>續高僧傳 Xù gāosēng zhuàn Continued Records of Eminent Monks Taishō</title><biblScope unit="page">551b-c</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl><bibl><ref target="#uuid-25494620-aead-4899-a45a-9bacaffb3139">YANAGIDA 1967</ref><title>初期禪宗史書の研究 Shoki zenshū shisho no kenkyū Studies on the Historical Works of the Early Period of Zen Buddhism</title><biblScope unit="page">487-489</biblScope><note><p/></note></bibl></listBibl></form><sense xml:id="uuid-499e3cf8-e193-4796-84b9-7423ef7c8aee"><gramGrp><pos>N</pos><tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func><tls:sem-feat corresp="#uuid-2e7204ae-4771-435b-82ff-310068296b6d">buddhist</tls:sem-feat></gramGrp><def>BUDDH: traditionally regarded as the founder of Chinese Chán/Zen Buddhism; skr. Bodhidharma (A number of works are attributed to him. However, there is little known about the life and actual teachings of this monk. For early biographic material see LUOYANG QIELAN JI 洛陽伽籃記, T.51/2092:1000b (tr. in MCRAE 1986: 17 and WANG 1984: 20-21) and XUGAOSENGZHUAN, T.50/2060: 551b-c (tr. in McRae 1986: 17-18). The only work which with some certainty can be attributed to him is the short ERRU SIZING LUN 二入四行論 ('Treatise on Two Entrances and Four Practices'); see YANAGIDA 1969 for an excellent annotated translation into Japanese). In addition there were a number of other works which traditionally had been attributed to Bodhidharma but which are of a later date, e.g. Dámó dàshī wùxìng lùn 達摩大師悟性論 [Treatise on the Nature of Enlightenment by Great Master Bodhidharma], Ānxīn fǎmén 安心法門 [The Dharma Gate of Pacifying the Mind]; Dámó chánshī lùn 達摩禪師論 [Treatise of Chán Master Bodhidharma]; Dámó dàshī wùxìng lùn 達摩大師悟性論 [Bodhidharma's Treatise on the Nature of Enlightenment]; Dámó dà-hī xuèmò lùn 達摩大師血脈論 [Treatise on the Blood Lineage of Bodhidharma]; Juè-guān lùn 絕觀論 [Treatise on the Transcendence of Cognition]. All these works are retrospectively attributed to Bodhidharma in order to firmly establish him as the First Chinese Patriarch. Bodhidharma was established as 'First Chinese Patriarch' in early Chán transmission texts like Fǎrú's 法如 epitaph (ed. in YANAGIDA 1967: 487-489; see also MCRAE 1986: 43-44, 85-86), the CFBJ and the LQSZJ. On Bodhidharma;s role in early Chán Buddhism see also Dumoulin 1951; for critical studies see FAURE 1986B; FAURE 1993: 130-135.The biographic entry on Bodhidharma in ZTJ is based on BLZ, fasc. 7 and 8 (fasc. 7, which must have included the first part of his biography, is not extant any longer).</def></sense></entry></div></div>